    en: "New York Criminal Procedure Law Section 440.10 allows a defendant to ask the court that entered a criminal judgment to vacate that judgment on grounds not fully raised or discoverable at trial or on direct appeal. Common grounds: newly discovered evidence that would probably have changed the outcome; constitutional violations (ineffective assistance of counsel, coerced confession, prosecutorial misconduct, Brady violation); invalid plea; actual innocence. The motion is filed in the original court, not on appeal. Criminal Procedure Law § 440.20 is the parallel motion to set aside an illegal sentence. Criminal Procedure Law § 440.30 handles DNA testing requests. No formal deadline to file Criminal Procedure Law § 440.10, though courts consider delay as a factor. A successful motion typically leads to a new trial or resentencing."
